&lt;h3 id=&#34;the-supernova-problem&#34;&gt;The Supernova Problem&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;aside class=&#34;notes&#34;&gt;
  The supernova community has put a lot of time and effort into high fidelity 3D models of explosion.  But at the end of the day, you spend months running these simulations and end up with one, or a handful of models.  These individual examples of success or failure do not illuminate the fundamental physics of explosion — we know that there is a &amp;ldquo;landscape&amp;rdquo; of explosion, where similar progenitors may have very different explosion properties.  So individual successful and failed explosions cannot easily distinguish between &amp;ldquo;successful&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;failed&amp;rdquo; failed explosions (i.e., models that shouldn&amp;rsquo;t explode, vs those that should).  So we need another approach
&lt;/aside&gt;
&lt;div class=body&gt;&lt;font size=6&gt;
If this steady state continues indefinitely, the PNS will collapse into a black hole.
&lt;p&gt;What revives the shock — Neutrino heating&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;How much heating is required to revive the shock?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Why do some models explode when others fail?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Physically, what distinguishes failed explosions from successful ones?&lt;/p&gt;


















