&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/section&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;an-antesonic-condition&#34;&gt;An &amp;ldquo;Antesonic&amp;rdquo; Condition&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;section&gt;
Simplest version of the problem: pressureless free-fall onto an isothermal gas


















&lt;figure &gt;


  &lt;a data-fancybox=&#34;&#34; href=&#34;https://mattjraives.github.io/img/model.png&#34; &gt;


  &lt;img src=&#34;https://mattjraives.github.io/img/model.png&#34; alt=&#34;&#34;  &gt;
&lt;/a&gt;



&lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;/section&gt;
&lt;section&gt;
Combine the Euler equations for isothermal accretion flow
$$v_r\frac{{\rm d}v_r}{{\rm d}r} = -\frac{1}{\rho}\frac{{\rm d}P}{{\rm d}r} - \frac{GM}{r^2}$$
with the shock jump conditions for pressureless free-fall onto a standing shock 
$$\rho_1v_1 = \rho_2 v_2$$
$$\rho_1v_1^2 + P_1 = \rho_2 v_2^2$$
and the resulting equations are valid only for
$$\frac{c_T^2}{v_{\rm esc}^2}\leq \frac{3}{16}$$
&lt;/section&gt;
